{{Infobox football league season |competition=Mongolia National Championship |season=1999 |winners= [[ITI Bank-Bars]] |continentalcup1= |continentalcup1 qualifiers= |relegated= |league topscorer= |biggest away win= |biggest home win= |highest scoring= |matches= |total goals= |longest wins= |longest unbeaten= |longest winless= |longest losses= |highest attendance= |lowest attendance= |average attendance= |prevseason=[[1998 Mongolia Premier League|1998]] |nextseason=[[2000 Mongolia Premier League|2000]] }}
The '''1999 Mongolian National Championship''' was the thirty-second recorded edition of top flight [[Association football|football]] in [[Mongolia]] and the fourth season of the [[Mongolian Premier League]], which took over as the highest level of competition in the country from the previous Mongolian National Championship.<ref name="RSSSF1">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesm/mongchamp.html |title=Mongolia&nbsp;– List of Champions |last1=Morrison |first1=Neil |last2=Zlotkowski |first2=Andre |last3=Kubusch |first3=Lars |last4=Batmunkh |first4=Jargalsaikhan |date=8 October 2015 |website=www.rsssf.com |publisher=[[RSSSF]] |access-date=22 December 2015}}</ref> [[ITI Bank-Bars]] were champions, their first (and to date only) title, [[Erchim]] were runners up, with [[Bajangol]] in third place.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesm/mong99.html |title=Mongolia 1999 |last1=Schöggl |first1=Hans |date=22 June 2004 |website=rsssf.com/ |publisher=[[RSSSF]] |access-date=6 January 2016}}</ref>
