==Production==
[[Bennett Miller]] began developing the project in 2010 after acquiring the rights to the story from Michael Coleman and Tom Heller.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/cannes-foxcatchers-bizarre-origin-story-701768|title=Cannes: 'Foxcatcher's' Bizarre Origin Story|author=Borys Kit|work=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> [[Megan Ellison]] financed the film through her [[Annapurna Pictures]], also producing alongside Miller, Jon Kilik, and Anthony Bregman.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jeff |last=Sneider |date=September 30, 2011 |title=Megan Ellison to finance 'Foxcatcher' |magazine=Variety |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118043717 |accessdate=October 20, 2012}}</ref> [[Sony Pictures Classics]] became the distributor, taking over from Sony's [[Columbia Pictures]], which had co-financed the film. Miller said "it's always been my hope and expectation that they (SPC) would distribute the film."<ref name="feinberg">{{cite news |first=Scott |last=Feinberg |date=August 15, 2013 |title='Foxcatcher' Jumps to Sony Pictures Classics; Release Date Set |magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/foxcatcher-jumps-sony-pictures-classics-602726 |accessdate=August 16, 2013}}</ref> [[Gary Oldman]] was first choice for the role of [[John E. du Pont]], but he turned down the role due to his commitment to ''[[Dawn of the Planet of the Apes]]''.

[[File:Cannes 2014 9.jpg|thumb|From left: Producers Jon Kilik and [[Megan Ellison]], [[Mark Ruffalo]], [[Channing Tatum]], director [[Bennett Miller]], and [[Steve Carell]] at the [[2014 Cannes Film Festival]]]]
Shooting began in the [[Pittsburgh metropolitan area]] on October 15, 2012, in and near the suburbs of [[Sewickley, Pennsylvania]], [[Sewickley Heights, Pennsylvania|Sewickley Heights]], and [[Edgeworth, Pennsylvania|Edgeworth]].<ref name="serafini">{{cite news|first=Kristina |last=Serafini |date=October 17, 2012 |title=Film crews back in Sewickley area |newspaper=[[Tribune-Review]] |url=http://triblive.com/neighborhoods/2780178-74/sewickley-movie-road-mcdaniel-crews-film-edgeworth-filmed-heights-shot |accessdate=October 18, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6CzAN8cO5?url=http://triblive.com/neighborhoods/2780178-74/sewickley-movie-road-mcdaniel-crews-film-edgeworth-filmed-heights-shot |archivedate=December 17, 2012 |deadurl=no |df=mdy }}</ref> With du Pont's mansion, Liseter Hall, having been demolished in January 2013, the filmmakers used [[Morven Park]], a historic estate in [[Leesburg, Virginia]] with a similar facade, for exterior filming.<ref>{{cite news |first=Crystal |last=Owens |date=October 15, 2012 |title=UPDATE: Movie magic at Morven Park? |newspaper=[[Loudoun Times-Mirror]] |url=http://www.loudountimes.com/index.php/news/article/movie_magic_and_morven_park898/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121014001843/http://www.loudountimes.com/index.php/news/article/movie_magic_and_morven_park898 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=October 14, 2012 |accessdate=October 31, 2012 }}</ref>  An 1899 mansion, [[Wilpen Hall]], in the wealthy Pittsburgh suburb of [[Sewickley Heights|Sewickley Heights, Pennsylvania]], served as Foxcatcher's stand-in for the interior filming location for du Pont's [[Philadelphia]]-area estate.<ref>{{cite news |date=October 15, 2012 |title=Another Big-Budget Movie Begins Filming Locally |publisher=[[CBS Pittsburgh]] |url=http://pittsburgh.cbslocal.com/2012/10/15/another-big-budget-movie-begins-filming-locally/ |accessdate=October 18, 2012}}</ref> Filming also took place in the Pittsburgh area communities of Rector ([[Ligonier Township, Westmoreland County, Pennsylvania|Ligonier Township]]), [[McKeesport, Pennsylvania|McKeesport]], [[White Oak, Pennsylvania|White Oak]], and [[Connoquenessing, Pennsylvania|Connoquenessing]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Deborah A. |last=Brehun |date=October 31, 2012 |title=Rector selected as locale for ‘Foxcatcher’ movie |newspaper=Tribune-Review |url=http://triblive.com/neighborhoods/yourligonier/2831859-74/pont-film-mizikar-movie-crew-foxcatcher-community-cottage-estate-january |accessdate=November 2, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=October 31, 2012 |title=McKeesport aflutter over Channing Tatum |publisher=[[WTAE-TV|WTAE]] |url=http://www.wtae.com/news/entertainment/McKeesport-aflutter-over-Channing-Tatum/-/9680792/17218030/-/lcxnmn/-/index.html |accessdate=October 31, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140111225635/http://www.wtae.com/news/entertainment/McKeesport-aflutter-over-Channing-Tatum/-/9680792/17218030/-/lcxnmn/-/index.html |archive-date=January 11, 2014 |dead-url=yes |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Jessica |last=Sinichak |date=November 15, 2012 |title=Nearby: Channing Tatum Filming ‘Foxcatcher’ in Butler County |publisher=[[Patch Media]] |url=http://sewickley.patch.com/articles/nearby-channing-tatum-filming-foxcatcher-in-butler-county |accessdate=November 15, 2012}}</ref> The production sought permission to film in West Mifflin Middle School in [[West Mifflin, Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Mary |last=Niederberger |date=August 23, 2012 |title=West Mifflin school may host movie crew again |newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]] |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/ae/movies/west-mifflin-school-may-host-movie-crew-again-650255/ |accessdate=November 12, 2012}}</ref> In December 2012, filming took place in [[Washington, Pennsylvania]], [[Trinity High School (Washington, Pennsylvania)|Trinity High School]], the [[Petersen Events Center]] in the Pittsburgh neighborhood of [[Oakland (Pittsburgh)|Oakland]], and the [[California University of Pennsylvania]] [[California University of Pennsylvania Convocation Center|Convocation Center]].<ref>{{cite news |date=December 7, 2012 |title=Filming to close Washington street |url=http://www.observer-reporter.com/article/20121207/BREAKING/121209480 |newspaper=[[Observer–Reporter]] |accessdate=December 9, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Rachel |last=Jones |date=January 25, 2013 |title=You Give Me Fever: Channing Tatum |url=http://whirlmagazine.com/you-give-me-fever/ |magazine=[[WHIRL Magazine]] |accessdate=April 13, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=December 11, 2012 |title=Pittsburgh extras needed for 'Foxcatcher' movie |url=http://www.wtae.com/news/entertainment/Pittsburgh-extras-needed-for-Foxcatcher-movie/-/9680792/17734544/-/i3kl9y/-/index.html |publisher=[[WTAE-TV|WTAE]] |accessdate=December 11, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140111224127/http://www.wtae.com/news/entertainment/Pittsburgh-extras-needed-for-Foxcatcher-movie/-/9680792/17734544/-/i3kl9y/-/index.html |archive-date=January 11, 2014 |dead-url=yes |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date= November 28, 2012 |title=Convocation Center to be Closed for Filming |url=http://www.calu.edu/news/press-releases/2012/11/convocation-center-closed-for-filming-dec.-16-23.htm |publisher=[[California University of Pennsylvania]] |accessdate=December 5, 2012}}</ref> Filming was scheduled to last through January 2013.<ref name="serafini"/>

The scene where the Foxcatcher team watches mixed martial arts on television in 1988 uses footage from [[Gary Goodridge]]'s win over Paul Herrera at [[UFC 8]], from February 1996. At [[UFC 9]] that March, Mark Schultz made his MMA debut, defeating Goodridge. In the film, he is depicted facing a fictional opponent. Channing Tatum stated that the role was "the hardest acting challenge I've had to date."<ref name="sneider">{{cite news |first=Jeff |last=Sneider |date=October 10, 2012 |title=Hall joins Carell in 'Foxcatcher' |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |url= http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118060581 |accessdate=October 18, 2012}}</ref>

==Release==
A release date for ''Foxcatcher'' was originally set for December 20, 2013. The date was postponed to allow for more time to complete the film, according to Sony Pictures Classics.<ref name="Release">{{cite web|title=Sony Pictures Classics Moves Foxcatcher Back to 2014|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=109471|work=comingsoon.net|publisher=[[CraveOnline]]|date=September 26, 2013|accessdate=September 26, 2013}}</ref> The film debuted at the [[2014 Cannes Film Festival]] in May 2014, in competition for the [[Palme d'Or]], the festival's highest prize,<ref>{{cite news |first=Justin |last=Chang |date=April 17, 2014 |title= Cannes Unveils 2014 Official Selection Lineup |magazine=Variety |url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/cannes-unveils-2014-official-selection-lineup-1201158710/ |accessdate=April 17, 2014}}</ref> where director Bennett Miller won the [[Best Director Award (Cannes Film Festival)|Award for Best Director]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/awardCompetition.html |title=Awards 2014 : Competition |accessdate=October 28, 2014 |publisher=[[Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]] |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023133531/http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/awardCompetition.html |archivedate=October 23, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref> The film made its way through the late-2014 festival circuit, appearing at the [[Telluride Film Festival|Telluride]], [[2014 Toronto International Film Festival|Toronto]], [[New York Film Festival|New York]], [[Vancouver International Film Festival|Vancouver]] and [[London Film Festival|London]] film festivals.<ref>{{cite web |first=Steve |last=Pond |date=September 8, 2014 |title=‘Foxcatcher’ Triumphs at Yet Another Film Festival |publisher=[[TheWrap]] |url=http://www.thewrap.com/foxcatcher-triumphs-at-yet-another-film-festival/ |accessdate=October 28, 2014}}</ref> ''Foxcatcher'' received a [[limited release]] on November 14, 2014.<ref>{{cite news |first=Katey |last=Rich |date=October 10, 2014 |title=Foxcatcher’s Director Explains Why It’s Actually a Funny Story
|magazine=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/vf-hollywood/2014/10/foxcatcher-new-york-film-festival |accessdate=October 28, 2014}}</ref> The film opened across U.S. theaters through December 2014 and January 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Foxcatcher |url=http://www.sonyclassics.com/foxcatcher/dates.html |accessdate=November 15, 2014 |publisher=[[Sony Pictures Classics]]}}</ref> The film was released on [[Blu-Ray]] and [[DVD]] March 3, 2015.

==Reception==

===Box office===
The film was given a [[limited release]] in North America on November 14, 2014, grossing $270,877 from 6 theaters, an average of $45,146 per theater. The film had its wide release on January 16, 2015, opening in 759 theaters and grossing $980,000, finishing 20th at the box office. Overall, ''Foxcatcher'' grossed $12.1 million in North America and $7.1 million in other territories for a total gross of $19.2 million, against its $24 million budget.<ref name="bom"/>

===Critical response===
''Foxcatcher'' received critical acclaim, with many praising the performances of Carell, Tatum, and Ruffalo.<ref name="Cannes Film Review: Foxcatcher">{{cite news|last1=Chang|first1=Justin|title=Cannes Film Review: 'Foxcatcher'|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/reviews/cannes-film-review-foxcatcher-1201185646/|accessdate=June 11, 2014|date=May 19, 2014|work=Variety}}</ref><ref name="indiewire.com">{{cite news|last1=Kohn|first1=Eric|title=Cannes Review: Channing Tatum Anchors Bennett Miller's Icy 'Foxcatcher,' But the Revelation is Steve Carell|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/cannes-review-channing-tatum-anchors-bennett-millers-icy-foxcatcher-but-the-revelation-is-steve-carrell|accessdate=June 11, 2014|date=May 19, 2014|work=IndieWire}}</ref> [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the film a rating of 88%, based on 232 reviews, with an average rating of 7.9/10. The site's critical consensus states, "A chilling true crime drama, ''Foxcatcher'' offers Steve Carell, Mark Ruffalo and Channing Tatum a chance to shine—and all three rise to the challenge."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/foxcatcher/|title=Foxcatcher|date=February 15, 2018|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]] the film has a score of 81 out of 100, based on 49 critics, indicating "universal acclaim".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/foxcatcher|title=Foxcatcher|publisher=Metacritic}}</ref>

Justin Chang of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' praised the film, writing: "[[Steve Carell]], [[Mark Ruffalo]] and [[Channing Tatum]] give superb performances in Bennett Miller's powerfully disturbing true-crime saga."<ref name="Cannes Film Review: Foxcatcher"/> Eric Kohn of ''[[Indiewire]]'' also reacted positively, with most of his praise going towards Carell's and Tatum's performances.<ref name="indiewire.com"/> Donald Clarke of ''[[The Irish Times]]'' praised Miller's direction, saying that "he [Miller] hits his stride with a stunning portrayal of psychopathy and moral decadence in the unlikely environment of Olympic wrestling."<ref>{{cite news|last1=Clarke|first1=Donald|title=Review: Foxcatcher|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/film/review-foxcatcher-1.1801619|work=The Irish Times|accessdate=June 11, 2014|date=May 19, 2014}} {{Paywall}}</ref> <!-- Review by Donald Clarke <ref name="it-clarke" /> --> Todd McCarthy of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' praised Carell's performance, calling it "career changing."<ref>{{cite news|last1=McCarthy|first1=Todd|title='Foxcatcher': Cannes Review|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movie/foxcatcher/review/705537|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=June 11, 2014|date=May 19, 2014}}</ref> Budd Wilkins of ''[[Slant Magazine]]'', however, gave the film a negative review, writing that it "offers us next to nothing of utility or complexity about du Pont's pathology."<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wilkins|first1=Budd|title=Cannes Film Festival 2014: Foxcatcher Review|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/house/2014/19/cannes-film-festival-2014-foxcatcher-review|accessdate=June 11, 2014|date=May 19, 2014}}</ref>

Mark Schultz's reaction to the movie has been varied due to the intensely personal subject matter. He supported the film in general throughout its creation and served as a consultant. At one point he became angry and criticized Bennett Miller after critics pointed out "homosexual undertones" in the portrayal of the relationship between Mark Schultz and du Pont. Schultz then demanded Miller address the issue "or I will."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/jan/02/mark-schultz-attacks-gay-relationship-in-wrestling-biopic-foxcatcher |author=Ben Child |date=January 2, 2015 |work=The Guardian |title=Mark Schultz attacks 'gay relationship' in wrestling biopic Foxcatcher}}</ref><ref name="it-clarke">{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/film/foxcatcher-review-carell-makes-a-passive-aggressive-nero-of-john-du-pont-1.2059069|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150109232826/http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/film/foxcatcher-review-carell-makes-a-passive-aggressive-nero-of-john-du-pont-1.2059069|title=Foxcatcher review: Carell makes a passive aggressive Nero of John Du Pont|archivedate=January 9, 2015|work=Irish Times}}</ref> Schultz said that "''Foxcatcher''{{'}}s scenes are mostly straight out of my book (except a few). But the relationships and personalities are complete fiction."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MarkSchultzy/status/549710019684347905|title=Mark Schultz on Twitter|work=Twitter}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/foxcatcher-movie-slammed-by-mark-schultz-2015-1?r=US|title='Foxcatcher' Movie Slammed By Wrestler Mark Schultz |date=January 2, 2015|work=Business Insider}}</ref> Several weeks after these statements, Schultz recanted criticisms of the movie, saying "''Foxcatcher'' is a miracle. I'm sorry I said I hated it. I love it," and apologized to Miller.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stern|first1=Marlow|title='Foxcatcher' Subject Mark Schultz Recants Criticisms: 'I Was Temporarily Insane'|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2015/01/18/foxcatcher-subject-mark-schultz-recants-criticisms-i-was-temporarily-insane.html|work=The Daily Beast|accessdate=January 19, 2015}}</ref>

