==Real-life subsequent events==
Following Dave Schultz's death, his widow, Nancy, and their two children moved to [[northern California]], where they still reside.<ref>Blumenthal, Jeff [http://www.bizjournals.com/philadelphia/news/2014/10/31/finally-free-of-john-du-pont-nancy-schultz-keeps.html "Foxcatcher Exclusive: Finally free of John du Pont, Nancy Schultz keeps her husband's legacy alive"] The Philadelphia ''Business Journal'', October 31, 2014</ref> In June 1997, Schultz was posthumously inducted into the [[National Wrestling Hall of Fame and Museum|U.S. National Wrestling Hall of Fame]].<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1955&dat=19970608&id=pT06AAAAIBAJ&sjid=6KYFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1366,5390704 Dave Schultz inducted in wrestling hall]. The Reading ''Eagle'', June 8, 1997, p. D10</ref> Mark Schultz stopped wrestling competitively after the [[1988 Summer Olympics|1988 Summer Olympic games]] and now lives in Oregon where he coaches wrestling and works for Keppler Speakers.<ref>[http://www.markschultz.com/ "Mark Schultz Olympic Wrestling Champion, Life Coach, Corporate Speaker, Author"] markschultz.com</ref> In November 1999, John du Pont agreed in an out-of-court settlement of the civil suit filed against him by Nancy Schultz to pay Dave's three surviving heirs "at least $35 million," the largest amount resulting from a U.S. wrongful-death suit ever paid directly by one person.<ref>Vigoda, Ralph [http://articles.philly.com/1999-11-27/news/25496054_1_david-schultz-nancy-schultz-du-pont "Schultz's Wife Settles Claim With Du Pont. The Multimillionaire Killed Wrestler David Schultz In 1996. He'll Pay $35 Million, Those Close To The Case Say."] The Philadelphia ''Inquirer'', November 27, 1999</ref>

A year after the shooting, du Pont, who had entered a plea of not guilty by reason of insanity, went on trial at the Delaware County Courthouse in [[Media, Pennsylvania]]. After three weeks of testimony followed by seven days of deliberation by the six-man, six-woman jury to consider eight distinct possible verdicts, on February 25, 1997 du Pont was found guilty but mentally ill of [[third-degree murder|murder in the third degree]]. He was subsequently sentenced by [[Pennsylvania courts of common pleas|Common Pleas]] Judge Patricia Jenkins to 13 to 30 years in prison. According to then-Delaware County District Attorney (now [[Member of Congress|MC]] R-PA7) [[Pat Meehan]], du Pont was the richest American ever tried for murder in the United States.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/US/9702/25/dupont.verdict/reax.html |title=Du Pont guilty but mentally ill in Olympic wrestler's murder. Widow to file civil suit against du Pont estate |publisher=CNN |date=November 25, 1997}}</ref><ref>"Du Pont Heir Found Guilty Of Murder but Mentally Ill: He Faces a Maximum Sentence of 20 Years," ''The New York Times'', February 26, 1997, p. A10</ref><ref>Pirro, J.F. [http://www.mainlinetoday.com/Main-Line-Today/November-2014/Online-Exclusive-John-du-Pont-Prosecutor-Talks/ "Online Exclusive: John du Pont Prosecutor Talks. '''Foxcatcher''', about the murder of Olympic wrestler Dave Schultz, debuts at Bryn Mawr Film Institute on Nov. 26"]. ''Main Line Today'', November 2014</ref> After a period of further psychiatric treatment at the [[Norristown State Hospital]], du Pont was eventually transferred first to [[State Correctional Institution – Cresson|Cresson State Correctional Institution]] near [[Altoona, Pennsylvania]] and later to [[Laurel Highlands State Prison]] in [[Somerset, Pennsylvania|Somerset]], where he died on December 9, 2010 at age 72. Both facilities were formerly state-run mental hospitals. At the time of his death from [[chronic obstructive pulmonary disease]], John du Pont had been incarcerated for murder for almost 15 years.<ref>"John E. du Pont 72, Dies; Killed Athlete," ''The New York Times'', December 10, 2010. p. 33</ref>

Foxcatcher Farm was eventually sold and the {{convert|1.25|sqmi|adj=on}} estate broken up for development. A {{convert|123|acre|ha|adj=on}} segment is now occupied by the campus of [[The Episcopal Academy]], a private independent [[K–12]] school founded in 1785, which moved there in 2008 from split campuses located in the nearby [[Philadelphia Main Line]] communities of [[Merion, Pennsylvania|Merion]] and [[Devon, Pennsylvania|Devon]].<ref>Gammage, Jeff [http://articles.philly.com/2007-10-21/news/25233421_1_episcopal-leaders-rohm-haas-campus "Episcopal Academy prepped for big change Expansion trumps angst over move from Merion"], ''Philadelphia Inquirer'', October 21, 2007</ref> The 90-year-old du Pont mansion, Liseter Hall, in which du Pont was raised and had lived for 57 years, was demolished in January 2013.<ref>Bannan, Pete [http://www.mainlinemedianews.com/articles/2013/01/25/main_line_suburban_life/news/doc510172af81da4619756296.txt "Historic DuPont mansion goes under the wrecker's ball"] ''Main Line Media News'', January 25, 2013.</ref> The mansion stood on a {{convert|400|acre|ha|-1|adj=on}} portion of the property that has now been developed by [[Toll Brothers]] into a "master planned community of 449 luxury homes" called "Liseter Estate."<ref>[http://www.prweb.com/releases/2012/11/prweb10145149.htm "Liseter Estate at Route 252 and Goshen Road in Newtown Square to be Developed by Toll Brothers"] PRWeb, November 20, 2012</ref>

